// utmctl. The CLI is a wrapper around the AppleScript interface, so it inherits every backend
// constraint. The three cli-help claims below all PASS -- and prove nothing about whether the
// feature works. Each is paired with the doc-contains claim that settles the backend question.
{"id": "utmctl-help-lists-exec", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "--help"], "expect": "exec", "claim": "utmctl advertises an `exec` subcommand. This says nothing about whether it works on an Apple-backend macOS guest -- see utmctl-exec-needs-qemu-guest-agent."}
{"id": "utmctl-help-lists-ip-address", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "--help"], "expect": "ip-address", "claim": "utmctl advertises an `ip-address` subcommand. It is AppleScript `query ip` and is guest-agent-gated, so it cannot report a macOS guest's IP -- see utmctl-exec-needs-qemu-guest-agent."}
{"id": "utmctl-start-help-lists-disposable", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "argv": ["utmctl", "start", "--help"], "expect": "--disposable", "claim": "TRAP: `utmctl start --help` advertises --disposable on every host, including one that can only run Apple-backend macOS guests. A flag in --help proves it parses, not that it works. The refutation is utmctl-disposable-is-qemu-only."}
{"id": "utmctl-is-an-applescript-wrapper", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/scripting/scripting/", "expect": "wrapper around the AppleScript interface", "claim": "utmctl is a wrapper around the AppleScript interface, not a second automation surface. Everything in section 2's suite-by-suite backend analysis therefore applies unchanged to the CLI."}
{"id": "utmctl-exec-needs-qemu-guest-agent", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/scripting/reference/", "expect": "QEMU guest agent must be running", "claim": "the AppleScript Guest Suite (execute / open file / query ip -- i.e. utmctl exec, file, ip-address) requires the QEMU guest agent, which an Apple-backend macOS guest does not have."}
{"id": "utm-guest-commands-need-guest-agent-v42", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/updates/v4.2/", "expect": "require QEMU guest agent to be installed", "claim": "corroborating source: the v4.2 release notes introduce the read/write-file, execute-command and list-IP commands for both the scripting interface and utmctl, and state they require the QEMU guest agent."}
{"id": "utm-input-automation-is-qemu-only", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/scripting/reference/", "expect": "Only supported on QEMU backend", "claim": "the AppleScript Input Automation Suite (input scan code / keystroke / mouse click) is QEMU-backend only."}
{"id": "utmctl-disposable-is-qemu-only", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/advanced/disposable/", "expect": "only supported on QEMU backend", "claim": "disposable mode is QEMU-backend only, so `utmctl start --disposable` cannot work for a macOS guest even though the flag parses. This is the refutation of utmctl-start-help-lists-disposable."}
{"id": "utmctl-usb-is-qemu-only", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/guest-support/sharing/usb/", "expect": "supported only by the QEMU backend", "claim": "USB sharing is QEMU-backend only, so the `utmctl usb` subcommands cannot work for a macOS guest."}
{"id": "utm-requires-app-open-for-headless", "kind": "doc-contains", "file": "specs/macos-ci/05-utm-automation.md", "site": "utm", "page": "/advanced/headless/", "expect": "UTM needs to be open while the headless virtual machine is running", "claim": "UTM.app must stay open for a headless VM, so utmctl presumes a GUI login session. This is why UTM is the interactive escape hatch and not the CI driver."}
